1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
 Duprović_Economy_Economy_Conferenze

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:29,000
 Good morning everyone, welcome to the 29th edition of the Dubrovnik Economic Conference. Many of you have been here before, some of you are here for the first time. So let me just give you a brief history of the conference. It started 29 years ago, we didn't skip any during the COVID, so that's important to mention.

3
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:58,000
 We even did it in 2020 and 2021, which means that it started during the war, which also means that there was a war in Europe before the Ukraine war, after the Second World War, which lasted five years, and we started just about the end of that war with the conference, and there is at least one person here, or two, who were there during the first conference, when the shells were still heard from the city.

4
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:27,980
 around, because the front line was very close by. It started as a conference on the transition, it was the time of the transition, but then after some years we transitioned out of the transition, and decided it doesn't make sense anymore to call it a transition conference, and now it's just a Dubrovnik Economic Conference. The difference this year is that for the first time we do it as a part of the Euro system, as we enter the

5
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:49,000
 in the Eurozone, as you know, on the 1st of January of this year, which is a great thing for us, but having the conference in Dubrovnik, I also have to say that Dubrovnik had a mint here, so-called Zeka, from 14th century until 19th century, and was minting a very appreciated currency at that time.

6
00:01:50,000 --> 00:02:11,000
 So it's not the first time we have a hard currency here. They had it before. Then we had a period when it was not that hard, and that's where we also learned what the inflation is and how it behaves, and that helps us a little bit today with understanding the inflation that we see.

7
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:32,000
 Dubrovnik was also a small open economy, but with a very solid state finance. Public finance was one of the strengths of the republic, and this is also something that I can talk a lot about, but I don't have time.

8
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:56,000
 But we learned also from them about the good policies in the small open economy, both in terms of the structural policies that they had, and I must say they had a policy of subsidizing the ship building here, which we inherited in the former Yugoslavia and Croatia, but it didn't work anymore.

9
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:04,000
 So you can do subsidies. If you do the subsidies in the right way, they work, actually. But if you do them in the wrong way, they don't work.

10
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:22,000
 We also have -- we had a 16th edition yesterday of the YES Young Economy Seminar, which we started then 16 years ago. Giovanni was there, a number of few, where we invite the papers from the Young Economists from the European Union.

11
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:44,000
 So out of the, I think, around 30 applications, we choose six papers that were presented yesterday. And I've heard that you've chosen also the winner paper, which we will announce tomorrow at the dinner and give a little award that we set up.

12
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:53,000
 So thanks for everyone who participated in the YES, and I'm glad that we have all the participants with us here.

13
00:03:53,000 --> 00:04:09,000
 For this conference, of course, we, every year, try, as you know, to be up to date, so to tackle the most important and contemporary issues.

14
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:18,000
 The first panel will deal, of course, with the question for all the central bankers, when will inflation converge back to the target.

15
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:34,000
 But we also have sessions on the labor market, why is it so resilient. We also will look at the interaction between the fiscal and monetary policies.

16
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:51,000
 And finally, we'll have a panel which was not planned initially. We planned to have a panel on the macroeconomic forecasting and the high-frequency micro data.

17
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:59,000
 But then, there was a Silicon Valley bank, there was a Credit Suisse, and then we said, OK, we cannot miss the banks this time.

18
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:16,000
 So we have a panel on the banking issues. We're going to ask the panel there on whether what we saw has happened a month ago, two months ago, is idiosyncratic, or we might have systemic problems.

19
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:29,000
 We also have a bunch of very interesting papers. We have a special keynote lecture on a broader perspective of the economic growth.

20
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:54,000
 We will be looking in one of the papers also at how the financing conditions affect the prices, which is one of the things that the ECB looks at when we decide on the interest rate hikes or not.

21
00:05:54,000 --> 00:06:03,000
 So I hope that over the next two days, we're going to have an interesting conference as usual.

22
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:09,000
 So with that, I would like to switch to our first panel.

23
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:22,000
 And I will start...

24
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:28,000
 Ah, yes. Yeah, yeah, yeah. Very good.

25
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:34,000
 Since we have become a member of the Euro system, we have new rules at the conference.

26
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:36,000
 The rules have changed.

27
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:41,000
 The panels are for the press.

28
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:50,000
 Panels are something, introductory statements that you can quote right away.

29
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:53,000
 It's fully open.

30
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:02,000
 But the Q&A we keep under the Chatham House rules, which means that in order to make the Q&A more interesting,

31
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:11,000
 that means that you can only quote the things from the Q&A if you later ask the panelists about the quote.

32
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:15,000
 So basically, you have to ask them after the panel what you can quote.

33
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:23,000
 But what is said in the introductory part of the panel, that's fully open.

34
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:36,000
 So let me start with the introduction to the panel.

35
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:44,000
 So very, very quickly, just to set the stage for the panel, I'm going to go through a few slides.

36
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:49,000
 One is the...

37
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:58,000
 If you remember last year, we had a panel on inflation as well with the central bankers from the central and east Europe.

38
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:05,000
 And we had a nice discussion between Jan Schwenner and the Czech Central Bank.

39
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:14,000
 If you remember, almost a fight, where Jan was saying that the Czech Central Bank was raising the rates too quickly.

40
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:24,000
 And he said that the reason why the inflation is so high in the Czech Republic is because they were increasing the rates so quickly.

41
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:27,000
 So then some people called it Erdogan argument.

42
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:39,000
 But what you see here is that really the central and east European countries started to raise rates much earlier as a response to the inflationary pressures

43
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:45,000
 than the advanced major central banks and economies.

44
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:55,000
 Now, much of the answer to this development of interest rates is probably in the interest rate parity argument.

45
00:08:55,000 --> 00:09:01,000
 because they have to care about the exchange rate while the large central banks don't.

46
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:09,000
 And Croatia is, in a way, lucky now because we were on the road to the euro already last year.

47
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:23,000
 So our interest rate and inflation development is much more like the eurozone than the Hungary, Czech Republic or Poland.

48
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:33,000
 And then if you look at the inflation development, we see that the headline is coming down,

49
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:40,000
 but that the underlying inflation pressures are still present.

50
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:48,000
 One thing that I will also ask the panelists is why did we miss so much in forecasts.

51
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:54,000
 If you look at the forecast errors from mid-21, they were large.

52
00:09:54,000 --> 00:10:04,000
 But in a way, I think it's something that you can expect because we had a discussion in the ECB.

53
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:06,000
 If anything, these errors are unbiased.

54
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:16,000
 So at the time when the inflation undershoots, we always predict it's going to be 2% when it overshoots.

55
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:20,000
 We always predict it's going to be 2% two years down the road.

56
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:30,000
 But, of course, when the deviation is higher, then the forecast errors are higher.

57
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:42,000
 The question, of course, now is how strong are underlying inflationary pressures.

58
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:52,000
 And we still see, if you look here at the three-month annualized price increases,

59
00:10:52,000 --> 00:11:03,000
 the food and services are where, if I look at this graph, it's questionable

60
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:11,000
 whether we're going to be with these pressures at 2% within the next two years.

61
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:13,000
 But this is a question for the panel.

62
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:19,000
 It's a luxury to be a chair, so I don't have to -- I can ask the questions rather than answer them.

63
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:33,000
 The monetary policy pass-through is there, but the pass-through is very different across the Eurozone countries.

64
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:39,000
 Here you can see the deposit betas, and you can see the pass-through on the credit rates.

65
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:54,000
 This is basically deposit and credit rates changes based on 1% increase in the policy rate.

66
00:11:54,000 --> 00:12:00,000
 And you can see that there's a lot of difference when you look at both time deposits

67
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:10,000
 and even more so when you look at the credit rates both to the corporates and the households,

68
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:20,000
 which might be a problem for a currency union if you have such a heterogeneity of the pass-through of the policy.

69
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:30,000
 So, one criterion that we look at when deciding on interest rates, which we said explicitly, is the also credit condition.

70
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:32,000
 We look at the BLS.

71
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:35,000
 This is the credit standards for corporates.

72
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:39,000
 And you can see that they have tightened significantly.

73
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:53,000
 If you look at the demand side, you see that the rate increases have had a significant effect on the demand,

74
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:57,000
 plus, of course, the slowdown in the economic activity.

75
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:07,000
 And on the supply side, you see that it's more risk perception than the costs of financing for the banks.

76
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:12,000
 That has an impact for the moment on the tightening of the credit standards.

77
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:24,000
 But we'll hear in the paper in the next session that it's not unambiguous how the credit standards might affect the prices.

78
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:37,000
 Because the paper will look at the financial shocks impact on the price decisions of the companies.

79
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:44,000
 In terms of the lending, we see a slowdown.

80
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:51,000
 But here we look at a little bit longer perspective, not last two years.

81
00:13:51,000 --> 00:14:00,000
 And when we look at the year-on-year growth of lending to corporate sector, or if you look at the momentum,

82
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:08,000
 I would say that the conclusion for me, at least, for the moment still, is not straightforward what's going on.

83
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:21,000
 Because if you look at the two countries within the eurozone, which had the slowest or negative rate of growth of credit to the corporates,

84
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:30,000
 they have had very low rates or negative for a long period of time, basically since the great financial crisis.

85
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:40,000
 So the question is, you know, whether it's something that is caused by the tightening of the monetary policy or it's maybe not.

86
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:47,000
 And if you look at the momentum, there you see that, again, if you take a longer perspective,

87
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:57,000
 it might not be that we are in a cyclically very different position than we were before, particularly because in the last reading,

88
00:14:57,000 --> 00:14:59,000
 you see actually momentum changing.

89
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:04,000
 So I would think we still need more data before we make firm conclusions.

90
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:07,000
 That's going to be also a question for the panel.

91
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:17,000
 Now, if you look at the expectations from the SMA, then this is the answer to the question of the panel.

92
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:27,000
 But I'm going to also -- Andras is laughing -- I'm going to ask the panel also whether they firmly believe in that

93
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:30,000
 and what are the risks to these expectations.

94
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:36,000
 Of course, the expectations of the monetary policy are then correlated with the expectations of the --

95
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:38,000
 on the inflation developments.

96
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:44,000
 The markets expect a relatively, I would say, quick monetary policy pivot at the moment.

97
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:51,000
 And finally, last point, which is more something for the last panel on the banks.

98
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:56,000
 That's the bank profitability and the financial market stress.

99
00:15:56,000 --> 00:16:01,000
 I would say this is less important in European case than the U.S.

100
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:11,000
 financial distress indicator comes down and the profitability of the banks in Europe goes up.

101
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:17,000
 And from what we see now is that the profitability of the banking system will be very high.

102
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:23,000
 Not only this year, but for the couple of years ahead of us.

103
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:31,000
 And I don't think that at the moment we should worry so much about the banks.

104
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:33,000
 But you never know.

105
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:39,000
 At the beginning of the year, I don't think people expected to see the problems that we saw later on.

106
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:48,000
 However, I think that the underlying situation in the European banking system is much better than we see across the Atlantic.

107
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:52,000
 And you can also see that the -- actually, return equity increases.

108
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:55,000
 It's a kind of secular trend of the increase in the return.

109
00:16:55,000 --> 00:17:08,000
 It's going to be just now boosted by the income that the banks will get from keeping this large excess liquidity with the central bank.

110
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:16,000
 And with that, I'm going to end my introductory statement.

111
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:27,000
 And we'll pass the floor to Giovanni Della Riccia, who will speak about the broad world picture rather than Europe.

112
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:48,000
 And then I'll switch to Philip to give us the view on Europe.

113
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:51,000
 Well, good morning, everybody.

114
00:17:51,000 --> 00:18:00,000
 And let me thank the governor and everybody else who contributed to the organization of this conference for the kind invitation.

115
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:04,000
 By the way, I was here yesterday at the Young Economist Conference.

116
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:08,000
 But to be specific, I was not one of the Young Economists.

117
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:09,000
 I'm sorry.

118
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:12,000
 I didn't win the prize either.

119
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:20,000
 So what I'm going to say just for the press in the room, this is not going to deviate much from the wheel

120
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:24,000
 that we released just about a month ago.

121
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:27,000
 So let me start.

122
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:35,000
 Since the last quarter of 2022 and first quarter of '23 activity has been recovering somewhat

123
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:42,000
 after the adverse shocks associated with Russia's invasion of Ukraine at the beginning of last year,

124
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:53,000
 confidence, however, remains quite low across both sides of the Atlantic.

125
00:18:53,000 --> 00:19:00,000
 This has been, you know, reflecting in labor markets that are still very tight.

126
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:11,000
 Here I'm plotting the change in the vacancy to unemployment ratios relative to just the last quarter before the pandemic.

127
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:20,000
 And you see that in many regions, this ratio is still very tight, especially in the United States.

128
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:29,000
 This reflects both resilient labor markets and an increase in activity, but also a shift in the beverage curve,

129
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:38,000
 which is not entirely explained, associated with sectoral shocks, but also maybe a loss in allocational efficiency.

130
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:51,000
 Because of this, inflation has been declining, especially the CPI, but it remains way above target.

131
00:19:51,000 --> 00:20:05,000
 And core inflation has proved very sticky, much stickier than expected, as Boris just showed in terms of forecast errors over the past few quarters.

132
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:24,000
 This in part is reflecting high services inflation as the economies reallocate resources and demand from goods to services with the reopening and the end of the pandemic.

133
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:41,000
 I would recommend everybody, this is off script from the Wii U, but Ben Bernanke and Olivier Blanchard just released what I consider a terrific paper on this topic about the United States.

134
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:48,000
 But I think it's really worth reading if you are interested in these issues.

135
00:20:48,000 --> 00:21:02,000
 From the policy perspective, central banks have been tightening monetary policy very aggressively and much faster than in the previous monetary policy cycle.

136
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:19,000
 Here on the left-hand side, we are charting the monetary policy tightening in this cycle vis-à-vis the one right before the GFC, and you see that it's an order of magnitude different.

137
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:29,000
 This has helped maintaining inflation expectations well anchored, both in advanced economies, emerging markets, and low-income countries.

138
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:37,000
 This has been a very synchronous tightening across the globe with very few deviations.

139
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:46,000
 And to some extent, this is contributing to keeping inflation in check as you have multiplying effects.

140
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:58,000
 Now, that said, until, I mean, as late as January of this year, at least for the United States,

141
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:05,000
 markets were not completely buying the story that the central bank was selling.

142
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:13,000
 And they were pricing the policy rate path well below what the Fed was communicating.

143
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:19,000
 Then in January -- and I don't know if on the screen is black or green.

144
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:20,000
 It was supposed to be green.

145
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:21,000
 It was supposed to be green.

146
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:32,000
 But in January, markets repriced the policy path upward in getting much closer to what the Fed was communicating.

147
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:35,000
 However, then we had SVB.

148
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:41,000
 We had a couple of other regional banks in the United States getting in trouble.

149
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:44,000
 We had the adverse event in Switzerland.

150
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:58,000
 And the policy rate path was repriced again, this time downward, with a major shift in expectations about where the policy rate would peak.

151
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:05,000
 And in the United States market started pricing actually some rate cuts for this year.

152
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:17,000
 Going back to the financial distress episode, this is to some extent the result of the very fast tightening of policy rate.

153
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:24,000
 And a financial sector that is coming out of a very, very long period of low rates.

154
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:42,000
 The question is -- and I think this is an open question and it's a question for the panel -- is how much equivalence you can make between tightening through a policy rate move and tightening through financial sector distress.

155
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:51,000
 So it's -- to some extent there is an equivalence in the sense that the spread between the policy rate and the lending rates goes up.

156
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:56,000
 And so there is less burden on the policy rate to contain inflation.

157
00:23:56,000 --> 00:24:01,000
 But the degree of uncertainty on the multipliers is much greater.

158
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:10,000
 So going back -- going to the forecast, what are the assumptions behind the most recent wheel of forecast?

159
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:24,000
 Well, first, we are updating our own policy rate path upward, reflecting the stickier-than-expected core inflation in many regions.

160
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:33,000
 We are also assuming that the fiscal stimulus associated with the pandemic is going to be withdrawn, but very, very gradually.

161
00:24:33,000 --> 00:24:45,000
 Now, from the point of view of side assumptions, we are assuming that the war in Ukraine is not going to get significantly worse.

162
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:56,000
 We are assuming that the reopening of China stays on track and that the financial distress that we just witnessed is not going to spread further.

163
00:24:56,000 --> 00:25:06,000
 So, based on those assumptions, we see growth bottoming out in 2023 at 2.8 percent globally.

164
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:17,000
 Bear in mind that this is a full one percentage point below average growth in the two decades preceding the pandemic, which was about at 3.8.

165
00:25:17,000 --> 00:25:21,000
 It was between 3.7 and 3.8 -- at 3.9.

166
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:28,000
 So it is low growth for this year and a very mild recovery next year.

167
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:35,000
 Unemployment in advanced economies will go up somewhat, and this will have spillovers on the rest of the world.

168
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:54,000
 In terms of inflation, which is the focus of the panel, we see inflation coming down in three-quarters of countries in 2023 -- so 75 percent -- from, I think, 8.7 to 7 percent on average.

169
00:25:54,000 --> 00:26:01,000
 But then, especially core, is going to stay high for a little bit longer.

170
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:07,000
 So we predict core to drop just a fraction of a point, then 0.2.

171
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:19,000
 And while next year most countries will be still above target, the deviation from target on average will be much smaller, about 1 percentage points.

172
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:28,000
 Most countries will go very close to target or at target in 2025.

173
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:37,000
 Risks to this scenario are relatively significant in terms of growth in the short run.

174
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:46,000
 Risks associated with a potentially much tighter financial conditions associated with balance sheet distress.

175
00:26:46,000 --> 00:26:54,000
 Risks to this scenario are absolutely the potential for the need for further hikes because of stickier than expected inflation.

176
00:26:54,000 --> 00:27:01,000
 Possible stress on sovereign debt markets in emerging and low-income countries.

177
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:04,000
 A possible slowdown in China.

178
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:15,000
 And an intensification of the war in Ukraine, all compounded by the trend that we are seeing in geo-economic fragmentation.

179
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:25,000
 From the point of view of inflation, in the short term, you know, we factor the risk of overshooting again, relative to expectations.

180
00:27:25,000 --> 00:27:28,000
 And then things should converge down.

181
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:34,000
 Now, I'm going to deviate from the wheel for just my last slide.

182
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:40,000
 And I just wanted to leave with some more cheerful comment.

183
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:54,000
 And I think that there are, if you look a little bit deeper, there are potential reasons for optimism in terms of avoiding much further, much longer inflation.

184
00:27:54,000 --> 00:28:02,000
 And this is not from fund war, so all disclaimers apply, please, to the press.

185
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:09,000
 There are obviously mitigating effects on wage pressures coming from war from home.

186
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:29,000
 This may apply more to the United States than Europe, but I've seen papers estimating premia up to 8% for people that would accept wages 8% lower in order to work from home and saving commuting costs and childcare and things like that.

187
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:34,000
 So this should help avoiding wage price spirals.

188
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:49,000
 Similarly, in a recent study has been shown that the role of profit margins relative to wages in this inflation episode is much larger than in the inflation episodes of the '70s.

189
00:28:49,000 --> 00:29:01,000
 And so, at least in theory, you would imagine that we can have some catch-up of real wages without that turning again into a push on prices.

190
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:13,000
 And finally, in one of the real chapters, we show that there is little reason to believe that in the long term, the natural rate of interest has moved much.

191
00:29:13,000 --> 00:29:22,000
 And so, there is a relatively high probability that we are going to go back to a situation pretty much like that in the Great Moderation.

192
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:27,000
 So, for the sake of time, I'll stop here and I think Phil is next.

193
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:28,000
 Thank you.

194
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:30,000
 Thank you.

195
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:36,000
 So, now we're going to zoom in on Europe.

196
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:37,000
 Philip?

197
00:29:43,000 --> 00:30:07,000
 So, I can give you an immediate answer.

198
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:11,000
 Inflation will return to target in a timely manner.

199
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:23,000
 And, of course, I share a lot of the points that were made by the first two speakers.

200
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:30,000
 But what I want to do is to go through the ingredients that we look at, which really are our three components.

201
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:38,000
 One is the outlook, which is basically a mix of the projections that the staff make.

202
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:41,000
 But also, the outlook is not just the most likely path.

203
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:43,000
 It's the risk outlook as well.

204
00:30:43,000 --> 00:30:52,000
 And we've listed in our recent meeting the list of upside risks and some downside risks that we would look at.

205
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:59,000
 The second component is to basically learn from what we actually see in the recent inflation data.

206
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:10,000
 because there is a lot of uncertainty and, in particular, the uncertainty about the intrinsic persistence of inflation.

207
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:18,000
 Because there was several pretty large shocks which, if you like, ignited inflation.

208
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:23,000
 And, you know, everything we know means that it doesn't kind of burn out overnight.

209
00:31:23,000 --> 00:31:32,000
 There's always going to be an impulse response function, if you like, a schedule where the adjustment does take time.

210
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:41,000
 But it should return to target, especially when inflation is above target, because we don't have a lower bound problem from above.

211
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:48,000
 And Boris, I think, was being a little bit semi-serious when he said the answer is always 2% two years from now.

212
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:55,000
 But that's kind of because that's, you know, we're not bystanders.

213
00:31:55,000 --> 00:32:05,000
 We do have a policy instrument to inject anti-inflationary pressure, to bring inflation back, as I said, in a timely manner.

214
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:13,000
 And I have the, let me be clear here, what I'm going to do in terms of the outlook is explain the March situation.

215
00:32:13,000 --> 00:32:19,000
 Now, in our May meeting, we basically said the March situation, as of now, is still relevant.

216
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:28,000
 So, in other words, from a European point of view, the excitement in the banking sector in March has not led to any kind of conclusive revisions.

217
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:34,000
 Now, of course, the forecasting process is ongoing for the June meeting.

218
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:41,000
 But, you know, I'm going to anchor what I say in terms of the outlook in terms of our March assessment.

219
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:46,000
 Now, it's a very interesting episode.

220
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:52,000
 As Giovanni just said, I mean, there are some unique features which come back to the pandemic,

221
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:57,000
 come back to the nature of a war and an energy shock and so on.

222
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:02,000
 So, you know, we rely a lot on historic examples.

223
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:04,000
 We rely a lot on econometric evidence.

224
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:09,000
 But you also have to say, okay, what are the special factors we need to take into account?

225
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:17,000
 And then it leads to issues about how can you have disinflation without a recession?

226
00:33:17,000 --> 00:33:21,000
 I mean, that's often a framing around the world.

227
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:26,000
 So, just a reminder about, you know, where we think GDP is.

228
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:28,000
 So, this graph, I think, is helpful.

229
00:33:28,000 --> 00:33:36,000
 So, the blue line is from the December 19 pre-pandemic projection.

230
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:48,000
 And compared to, you know, indexing GDP to 100 at the end of 19, it said this is the boring but kind of positive path the area economy will be on.

231
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:51,000
 That was the expectation in 2019.

232
00:33:51,000 --> 00:33:56,000
 And then, of course, the pandemic came along and there's a huge hit to output.

233
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:59,000
 On the other hand, there's been fairly rapid bounce back from that.

234
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:03,000
 And then the orange line is from the point of December 21.

235
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:08,000
 So, a year and a half ago before the war, this is what we thought was coming next.

236
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:18,000
 Which is essentially a rapid recovery, especially in 22, also in 23, and will be more or less back in the pre-pandemic trend.

237
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:22,000
 Then, with the war, that has been shaken.

238
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:28,000
 And now, even though it looks better in March than it did in December with the reverse of the terms of trade shock,

239
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:35,000
 we do basically have a path for GDP, which is very far away from the pre-pandemic trend.

240
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:39,000
 There's some element of that is a revision to potential output.

241
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:46,000
 But part of that is basically there is still a reopening of the European economy, a recovery from the pandemic.

242
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:50,000
 And this explains why the European economy should grow over time.

243
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:56,000
 And the fact that we grew very little last year, there's going to be pretty subdued growth this year,

244
00:34:56,000 --> 00:34:59,000
 is creating, if you like, the disinflation space.

245
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:05,000
 It's growing slowly compared to what the European economy should be growing like in this recovery phase.

246
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:11,000
 So, the basic economics, there's a connection between disinflation and subdued activity, is there.

247
00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:15,000
 It's just you have to kind of make the appropriate adjustment.

248
00:35:15,000 --> 00:35:20,000
 The same basic points relates to consumption and investment.

249
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:23,000
 And this is where there's a very big difference to the U.S.

250
00:35:23,000 --> 00:35:29,000
 We didn't have this surge, you know, going above the pre-pandemic trend, which was true in the U.S.

251
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:40,000
 But basically it says, you know, if consumption has flat lined in recent months, we think it's going to grow fairly slowly in the near term.

252
00:35:40,000 --> 00:35:45,000
 But there will be ongoing momentum because the European economy still has a lot of bounce back to do.

253
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:49,000
 Okay, so then where does that take us to inflation?

254
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:53,000
 And I've been using this graph because I think it captures quite a bit.

255
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:59,000
 So the solid blue line is headline, which we know has come, you know, went to this spectacular peak and has come down.

256
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:01,000
 But it's still pretty high.

257
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:05,000
 The shaded blue area is the range of measures of underlying inflation.

258
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:15,000
 And underlying inflation in our world is supposed to basically say, where do we think inflation is going to be a year from now, let's say, or two years from now?

259
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:21,000
 And that's saying as some number between four and seven.

260
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:35,000
 So then how do our own forecasts and the different symbols are our forecasts, the survey of monetary analysts, the market-based measures, all of those basically say we don't believe the underlying inflation numbers.

261
00:36:35,000 --> 00:36:38,000
 We believe there's extra disinflation coming.

262
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:45,000
 So they have -- there's some range of variation by 2024, exactly how quickly.

263
00:36:45,000 --> 00:36:50,000
 But there's a pretty solid view by 2025, inflation will be around two.

264
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:54,000
 So it remains, you know, a lot to discuss.

265
00:36:54,000 --> 00:37:00,000
 And, of course, in the fine detail for monetary policy, it's very relevant for where exactly we go.

266
00:37:00,000 --> 00:37:10,000
 But there is a basic question of, okay, you know, tell me why these underlying inflation measures need some downward correction.

267
00:37:10,000 --> 00:37:13,000
 Why can't we just take them at face value?

268
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:17,000
 And I'll come down in a minute.

269
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:29,000
 But just very quickly, in terms of the components of inflation, because, you know, economically, we think what determines inflation in the traded sector is very different to what determines inflation in the non-traded sector.

270
00:37:29,000 --> 00:37:36,000
 What determines inflation in relation to basically durables would be different to non-durables and so on.

271
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:43,000
 So that overall return of inflation to 2% has very different dynamics for different sectors.

272
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:51,000
 I mean, for energy, is energy inflation going to zero this year on average, which is right now a big negative number.

273
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:59,000
 For food, it's important because I think Giovanni had essentially a lot of peaking in 2022 globally.

274
00:37:59,000 --> 00:38:08,000
 But actually, for food and for CORE, for us, the peak is this year, not last year, because there is a kind of handover from our lag effects.

275
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:11,000
 So we're on an annual basis.

276
00:38:11,000 --> 00:38:12,000
 This is the peak year.

277
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:18,000
 But, of course, it would be nice to move beyond the peak to have the reassurance that these are coming down.

278
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:20,000
 And the same for CORE.

279
00:38:20,000 --> 00:38:32,000
 As Giovanni said, I mean, one of the big issues is, you know, there's two different profit dynamics to keep track of.

280
00:38:32,000 --> 00:38:44,000
 One is in the pandemic itself with the lockdowns, the surge in demand for goods globally, and the supply bottlenecks did create an amazing profit opportunity.

281
00:38:44,000 --> 00:38:47,000
 And then there's a second phase when the European economy reopened.

282
00:38:47,000 --> 00:38:56,000
 Then the services sector, which was, you know, was not making money in the pandemic as such, except to maybe government transfers.

283
00:38:56,000 --> 00:39:05,000
 In the last nine months of last year and the opening of this year, the services sector has seen a resumption of demand.

284
00:39:05,000 --> 00:39:10,000
 And there are supply constraints, which were most intense last year, which helped to build up profits.

285
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:25,000
 And, again, to the extent that this surge in profitability should not be maintained, it does mean wage increases and so on should not pass one-for-one into higher prices this year.

286
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:35,000
 And so, as an example, also, even within services, the reopening sectors are disproportionately contributing a lot at the moment.

287
00:39:35,000 --> 00:39:43,000
 So, if you connect travel, tourism, and restaurants, their contribution to inflation over the last year has been way above normal.

288
00:39:43,000 --> 00:39:48,000
 And this is one of the open questions about, is this going to normalize?

289
00:39:48,000 --> 00:39:54,000
 And then we highlight with restaurants, there's a tight connection between restaurant prices and food prices.

290
00:39:54,000 --> 00:40:00,000
 So, the high food inflation we're seeing will also be maintaining restaurant inflation.

291
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:08,000
 And, again, we have food inflation reversing later this year and, in turn, may help to calm down restaurant prices.

292
00:40:08,000 --> 00:40:16,000
 On the right side, you know, because the national account data are lagging and so on, we learn a lot from just asking firms directly.

293
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:22,000
 And in our corporate telephone survey, what they said most recently is the blue line said, yes, we made a lot of money last year.

294
00:40:22,000 --> 00:40:26,000
 And the orange line is saying, that's not going to persist this year.

295
00:40:26,000 --> 00:40:32,000
 We have rising costs this year from wages, but we don't have the same pricing power as we had last year.

296
00:40:32,000 --> 00:40:38,000
 So, there is going to be this contribution, we think, from the compression of profits.

297
00:40:38,000 --> 00:40:42,000
 Wages play a very important role.

298
00:40:42,000 --> 00:40:52,000
 And, again, explaining why, even though the original shock to energy is reversed, the pandemic, the bottlenecks are reversing, the pandemic reopening should ease over time.

299
00:40:52,000 --> 00:40:56,000
 What we have is there is a catch-up process.

300
00:40:56,000 --> 00:41:02,000
 So, real wages, even this year, will remain below their 2019 levels.

301
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:10,000
 So, even though the labour market is tight in many European countries, the shock to real wages last year from surprise inflation was so big.

302
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:16,000
 And the way the labour market is sufficiently inertial, it doesn't correct all at once.

303
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:18,000
 It's a gradual process.

304
00:41:18,000 --> 00:41:24,000
 But, crucially, for disinflation, what we have is a negative slope.

305
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:30,000
 So, the left side is nominal wages, which are going way above normal for the next several years.

306
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:37,000
 But, basically, the most intense wage correction is this year, because the real wage gap is largest this year.

307
00:41:37,000 --> 00:41:44,000
 So, on average, for the year area, it has nominal wages going above 5% this year, 4-something next year,

308
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:49,000
 and 3-something in 25, all above steady state.

309
00:41:49,000 --> 00:41:54,000
 But, all of that only brings real wages back to 2019 levels in 25.

310
00:41:54,000 --> 00:41:56,000
 So, we do think there's upside risk to this.

311
00:41:56,000 --> 00:41:58,000
 This is a judgement.

312
00:41:58,000 --> 00:42:08,000
 It's a judgement that, you know, when you take your area as a whole, you know, is, I think, a reasonable judgement.

313
00:42:08,000 --> 00:42:13,000
 But, it's also reasonable to say, well, let's see what the data will tell us.

314
00:42:13,000 --> 00:42:18,000
 On the right side, we have this wage tracker data, and it's telling us two things.

315
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:23,000
 Basically, on average, wages are rising in a very moderate way.

316
00:42:23,000 --> 00:42:26,000
 Many people are still locked into old contracts.

317
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:29,000
 They're not being renegotiated, you know, instantly.

318
00:42:29,000 --> 00:42:34,000
 So, the overall wage dynamic remains moderate.

319
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:39,000
 The orange line is telling you the latest deal, which might be a good hint towards the future.

320
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:43,000
 And, the latest deal is coming in as, you know, above 5%.

321
00:42:43,000 --> 00:42:46,000
 But, ballpark, it's what we expect.

322
00:42:46,000 --> 00:42:48,000
 And, remember, there's lots of differences.

323
00:42:48,000 --> 00:42:54,000
 Boris had lots of differences across countries, and this is one area where there are differences across countries.

324
00:42:54,000 --> 00:43:07,000
 But, remember, what we essentially have is the overall inflation rate will be rising services inflation, declining goods inflation, declining food inflation.

325
00:43:07,000 --> 00:43:09,000
 So, it's a handover process.

326
00:43:09,000 --> 00:43:11,000
 So, this is in the March forecast.

327
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:17,000
 We go back to 2% price inflation, even though wage inflation is elevated for several years.

328
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:25,000
 The labor market, you could say, well, it looks so tight, you know, why do you not have much stronger wage pressure?

329
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:29,000
 Because, essentially, what we have is just this catch-up dynamic.

330
00:43:29,000 --> 00:43:36,000
 It's basically mostly reflecting the restoring real wages, not that there's a big increase in real wages.

331
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:42,000
 And, this is a bit different to the Blanchard-Bernanke study that Giovanni was referring.

332
00:43:42,000 --> 00:43:51,000
 And, the answer is on the right side, which is basically, part of the recovery in Europe is a big recovery in the labor force, including a lot of immigration.

333
00:43:51,000 --> 00:43:55,000
 So, over the last year, employment has grown very strongly.

334
00:43:55,000 --> 00:44:00,000
 But, indicators of labor market tightness, like vacancies or unemployment, have not moved.

335
00:44:00,000 --> 00:44:02,000
 In fact, vacancies have slightly eased.

336
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:09,000
 So, in other words, if you add in a big labor supply positive effect, that helps to reconcile.

337
00:44:09,000 --> 00:44:13,000
 And, I would also join the conjecturing about working from home.

338
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:17,000
 One reason, because we're seeing a lot of older workers rejoin the labor force.

339
00:44:17,000 --> 00:44:20,000
 And, my bet is working from home helps with that.

340
00:44:20,000 --> 00:44:26,000
 This is just to say, the bottlenecks are easing, the energy shock is reversing.

341
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:28,000
 So, I won't stop on that.

342
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:30,000
 And, I don't want to overrun time.

343
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:43,000
 So, Sabaris made the point about momentum, which is basically, momentum in relation to goods inflation, fruit inflation, and service inflation is still pretty high.

344
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:46,000
 So, it's not the case right now.

345
00:44:46,000 --> 00:44:50,000
 So, I'm saying we expect to turn the corner.

346
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:55,000
 But, I wouldn't say we've exactly left that corner quite yet.

347
00:44:55,000 --> 00:45:01,000
 And then, if you look at the underlying inflation, you might say, well, there's some kind of temporary factors there.

348
00:45:01,000 --> 00:45:03,000
 Let's look at the underlying measures.

349
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:09,000
 In relation to the underlying measures, some of them do see more of a drop in terms of momentum.

350
00:45:09,000 --> 00:45:12,000
 But, some of them are still pretty high.

351
00:45:12,000 --> 00:45:14,000
 So, it's a mixed picture.

352
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:23,000
 Let me – maybe I'll also say in relation to core, because there's this phrase going around, core is sticky.

353
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:28,000
 I don't really think this is the best analytical way to think about it.

354
00:45:28,000 --> 00:45:32,000
 First of all, there's a big difference between goods inflation and services inflation.

355
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:39,000
 And, second, one reason why core went up so much was every sector had to reprice because of the scale of the energy.

356
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:42,000
 Now, the energy price has reversed.

357
00:45:42,000 --> 00:45:44,000
 You know, I don't think it's symmetric.

358
00:45:44,000 --> 00:45:53,000
 But, all the analysis does say over many years, when energy prices fall, core inflation does follow.

359
00:45:53,000 --> 00:45:57,000
 Because, there is less pressure from energy costs.

360
00:45:57,000 --> 00:45:59,000
 There's less pressure on the cost of living.

361
00:45:59,000 --> 00:46:01,000
 And, therefore, our nominal weight increases.

362
00:46:01,000 --> 00:46:08,000
 So, we do think these spectacular reversal of energy prices will feed into lower core.

363
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:11,000
 But, the timeline for that and the scale of it is uncertain.

364
00:46:11,000 --> 00:46:16,000
 Okay, let me finish just quickly with the most basic point.

365
00:46:16,000 --> 00:46:24,000
 But, maybe I'm being a bit obtuse about the title of the seminar, which is, it's not all about exogenous processes.

366
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:26,000
 There is a policy lever.

367
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:29,000
 And, the policy lever we've used quite a bit.

368
00:46:29,000 --> 00:46:33,000
 So, in December 21, the orange line is what people thought.

369
00:46:33,000 --> 00:46:34,000
 Low for long.

370
00:46:34,000 --> 00:46:40,000
 The policy rates would be only converging towards zero from below, even in 2025.

371
00:46:40,000 --> 00:46:42,000
 We're not in that world.

372
00:46:42,000 --> 00:46:50,000
 And, that amount of tightening, we're seeing it in house prices.

373
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:52,000
 We're seeing it in credit dynamics.

374
00:46:52,000 --> 00:46:56,000
 You know, we're seeing it in flat consumption.

375
00:46:56,000 --> 00:47:00,000
 We're seeing it in the slowdown in construction investment.

376
00:47:00,000 --> 00:47:05,000
 But, we do also have to do a lot of filtering for the reasons Boris said.

377
00:47:05,000 --> 00:47:07,000
 It's an unusual period.

378
00:47:07,000 --> 00:47:09,000
 The pandemic is not a baseline.

379
00:47:09,000 --> 00:47:14,000
 The pre-pandemic is not a baseline either, because we had a lot of deleveraging before the pandemic.

380
00:47:14,000 --> 00:47:16,000
 And, we had a low inflation problem.

381
00:47:16,000 --> 00:47:23,000
 So, working out what is a reasonable kind of baseline to think about is, of course, part of our work.

382
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:27,000
 And, again, this is just telling you it's passing through.

383
00:47:27,000 --> 00:47:31,000
 Let me make a comment about credit standards on this channel.

384
00:47:31,000 --> 00:47:41,000
 Because, you know, Giovanni said, look, you know, there's some kind of mapping from financial conditions in general into policy rates.

385
00:47:41,000 --> 00:47:47,000
 How the financial conditions tighten is maybe secondary to the fact they are tightening.

386
00:47:47,000 --> 00:47:58,000
 But, at the ECB, we do think it's credit, especially a bank-based system, doesn't just work through the yield curve or through lending rates.

387
00:47:58,000 --> 00:48:10,000
 Quantity restrictions do directly affect, basically, the ration credit and they have a visible impact on GDP levels.

388
00:48:10,000 --> 00:48:15,000
 So, there's a kind of macro channel, not just through the interest rates.

389
00:48:15,000 --> 00:48:16,000
 Okay.

390
00:48:16,000 --> 00:48:24,000
 So, let me stop there by basically saying, given all of these reasons, this is why our policy guidance is so precise.

391
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:33,000
 We say we need to look at the -- it remains the case the anchor of the system is the projections.

392
00:48:33,000 --> 00:48:35,000
 That brings all of these things together.

393
00:48:35,000 --> 00:48:39,000
 The judgment calls yes, so it's not the only thing we look at.

394
00:48:39,000 --> 00:48:46,000
 But the projections, the outlook, and not just the base case, but also the risk outlook is important.

395
00:48:46,000 --> 00:48:51,000
 It's important to accept that the persistence of inflation is uncertain.

396
00:48:51,000 --> 00:49:00,000
 So, we do have to observe and absorb what we learned from the filtered -- the underlying filter of the latest inflation data.

397
00:49:00,000 --> 00:49:03,000
 And we also have not tightened that very often.

398
00:49:03,000 --> 00:49:10,000
 So, we also accept this uncertainty about the strength of monetary policy transmission and feedback from that.

399
00:49:10,000 --> 00:49:13,000
 And all of that in context where there's lots of lags in the system.

400
00:49:13,000 --> 00:49:20,000
 So, what we've done so far, how much disinflation we've already injected, we'll have to keep an eye on.

401
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:24,000
 So, I'm sure there's still plenty of room.

402
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:26,000
 I haven't answered the question conclusively there.

403
00:49:26,000 --> 00:49:30,000
 So, I'm sure the rest of the panel will finish the job now.

404
00:49:30,000 --> 00:49:31,000
 So, thank you.

405
00:49:31,000 --> 00:49:33,000
 Thank you, Coach.

406
00:49:38,000 --> 00:49:40,000
 So, let's move to the BIS now.

407
00:49:40,000 --> 00:49:42,000
 Marco Lombardi is with us here.

408
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:49,000
 The BIS has recently published a paper on the inflation, on the two regime of the inflation.

409
00:49:49,000 --> 00:49:56,000
 So, I'm sure Marco will give us a view of how the BIS thinks about it.

410
00:49:56,000 --> 00:50:01,000
 Although, he will say that these are his personal, probably, views rather than institutional.

411
00:50:01,000 --> 00:50:02,000
 Yeah.

412
00:50:02,000 --> 00:50:03,000
 Thanks.

413
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:07,000
 Thanks very much for inviting me to this very distinguished panel.

414
00:50:07,000 --> 00:50:09,000
 I'm really honored to be here.

415
00:50:09,000 --> 00:50:13,000
 So, yeah.

416
00:50:13,000 --> 00:50:20,000
 So, what I'm going to talk about today is a two regime view of inflation.

417
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:29,000
 And in spite of this being joint work with Claudio Borio and other BIS colleagues, James Yetmond and Degon Zakracek,

418
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:35,000
 this is not really to be taken as the BIS view on the matter of inflation.

419
00:50:35,000 --> 00:50:47,000
 Even though, I should say that this, what I'm going to present today, largely reflects last year's annual economic report, which you can check for your reference.

420
00:50:47,000 --> 00:51:06,000
 So, what we did in this work is to try to characterize the inflation process in terms of two regimes to be able to shed light on the recent puzzle, if you want, of more persistent than expected inflation.

421
00:51:06,000 --> 00:51:13,000
 And this is a simple outline of how we characterize these two regimes.

422
00:51:13,000 --> 00:51:26,000
 In a low inflation regime, aggregate inflation, HICP or CPI, is largely the result of independent sectoral price movement, largely independent across each other.

423
00:51:26,000 --> 00:51:41,000
 This means that these unrelated movements in sectoral prices generate relative price changes across the different goods, but have little commonality among themselves.

424
00:51:41,000 --> 00:51:57,000
 This also implies that all these sectoral price changes, given that they happen randomly in this regime, they tend to cancel each other and therefore have only transitory impact on aggregate inflation readings.

425
00:51:57,000 --> 00:52:09,000
 And even more importantly, that this type of inflation does not really feed into wage demands from the side of workers.

426
00:52:09,000 --> 00:52:12,000
 So, there are two reasons why we think this is the case.

427
00:52:12,000 --> 00:52:22,000
 One is that when inflation is low, agents can be inattentive to inflation, even in a rational way.

428
00:52:22,000 --> 00:52:36,000
 And the second is that when inflation is low and driven mainly by relative price changes, it could be the case that different actors in the economy, based on their different consumption basket,

429
00:52:36,000 --> 00:52:40,000
 they face very different personal inflation rates.

430
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:52,000
 And so, the aggregate inflation rate does not really represent the increases in the cost of living of all workers, nor in the cost of input for firms.

431
00:52:52,000 --> 00:53:03,000
 This environment is very benign for monetary policy, because monetary policy can afford quite a great deal of flexibility in that world.

432
00:53:03,000 --> 00:53:21,000
 By flexibility, I mean that if inflation is stable, mainly driven by this idiosyncratic sectoral price changes, policymakers can tolerate moderate, if not too persistent, deviations from the inflation target.

433
00:53:21,000 --> 00:53:26,000
 On the other hand, things are very different in a high inflation regime.

434
00:53:26,000 --> 00:53:33,000
 In a high inflation regime, aggregate inflation reflects most of the prices moving together in the same direction.

435
00:53:33,000 --> 00:53:53,000
 If you want, if you allow me a more academic take on this, there's a very nice research by Rice and Watson in which they labeled this sort of inflation where all prices move at the same time by the same amount as pure inflation.

436
00:53:53,000 --> 00:54:00,000
 In this world, prices move together, so there's high commonality across price changes.

437
00:54:00,000 --> 00:54:08,000
 And importantly, there's stronger and more extensive price spillovers across different categories.

438
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:11,000
 And stronger feedbacks between wages and prices.

439
00:54:11,000 --> 00:54:22,000
 Because in this world, the aggregate inflation rate becomes more of a coordinating device, according to which both workers and firms set their own demands.

440
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:34,000
 This is, of course, a challenging world for monetary policy, and here prompt and forceful monetary policy reaction to this type of inflation is called for.

441
00:54:34,000 --> 00:54:44,000
 So let me now bring to the table some empirical insights on how we can characterize these two regimes.

442
00:54:44,000 --> 00:54:52,000
 And the first piece of evidence I want to touch upon is the role of a common factor underlying inflation.

443
00:54:52,000 --> 00:54:57,000
 In these two graphs, you see a bunch of lines.

444
00:54:57,000 --> 00:55:00,000
 The black one is the most important one.

445
00:55:00,000 --> 00:55:09,000
 That's the percentage of the variance that the common factor of inflation explains the variance of all sectoral price changes.

446
00:55:09,000 --> 00:55:13,000
 The left-hand panel is for the US, and the right-hand panel is for Mexico.

447
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:20,000
 For Mexico, we picked these two countries because there's decent sector data coverage in that.

448
00:55:20,000 --> 00:55:27,000
 And you can see that in both cases, the black line declines together with the level of inflation.

449
00:55:27,000 --> 00:55:31,000
 That's the orange dashed line in the graph.

450
00:55:31,000 --> 00:55:39,000
 So that happens roughly in the mid-90s for the US, much later, after 2010 for Mexico.

451
00:55:39,000 --> 00:55:48,000
 And interestingly, if you see in Mexico, the decline of the relevance of the common component starts when inflation crosses the 10% threshold.

452
00:55:48,000 --> 00:55:56,000
 So if you want to say that in other words, when the central bank has established some credibility in fighting inflation.

453
00:55:56,000 --> 00:56:04,000
 Now let me move to another feature that distinguishes high and low inflation regime, and that's the inflation volatility.

454
00:56:04,000 --> 00:56:13,000
 Now this is well known and well documented that the high inflation regime is associated with high volatility of inflation.

455
00:56:13,000 --> 00:56:23,000
 This is pictured here in the graphs where the total variance of inflation is the black line.

456
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:36,000
 What is a bit less appreciated is the fact that when inflation declines and is brought under control by the central bank, so you want to say,

457
00:56:36,000 --> 00:56:46,000
 the decline in the volatility of inflation is driven mainly by a decline in the covariance of the sector price development,

458
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:53,000
 rather than by a decline in the individual variances of sector price changes.

459
00:56:53,000 --> 00:57:00,000
 So all this reduction in the volatility of inflation is mainly due to less commonality across price changes,

460
00:57:00,000 --> 00:57:08,000
 which sits nicely with our story of, with our characterization of the low inflation regime.

461
00:57:08,000 --> 00:57:20,000
 Finally, what happens in a low inflation regime compared to a high inflation regime is a reduction in the cross-sectoral price spillovers.

462
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:31,000
 Here, these two graphs represent, these two matrices represent a way to measure spillovers across PC sectors in the US.

463
00:57:31,000 --> 00:57:39,000
 And you see two estimates. The one on the left is based on a period of high inflation, 69 to 84.

464
00:57:39,000 --> 00:57:46,000
 The one on the right is on a period of lower inflation. It goes up to 2019.

465
00:57:46,000 --> 00:57:55,000
 The first thing I want to draw your attention on is that the matrix on the right-hand side is much less colored than the one on the left,

466
00:57:55,000 --> 00:58:04,000
 signaling that there is less spillovers from one PC sector to the other.

467
00:58:04,000 --> 00:58:17,000
 The second thing that I think it's interesting to remark is that while in the left-hand panel the matrix has dark colors a bit all over the place,

468
00:58:17,000 --> 00:58:28,000
 which means that meaning that these spillovers are pervasive and go from all categories to from and transmit from all most categories of the PC prices.

469
00:58:28,000 --> 00:58:34,000
 In the right-hand panel, the spillovers are concentrated in two columns.

470
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:40,000
 You see the one, the darker ones, one being food and the other one being gasoline.

471
00:58:40,000 --> 00:58:49,000
 And interestingly, the darkest element there is food to food services, which is what Philip just mentioned.

472
00:58:49,000 --> 00:58:59,000
 Okay, so take away from this graph, a low inflation regime, there is less cross transmission of shocks between the sectors.

473
00:58:59,000 --> 00:59:11,000
 So in general, shock originating in one specific sector is much less pervasive than in a high inflation regime.

474
00:59:11,000 --> 00:59:22,000
 Now let me move to the other key element that drives the inflation persistence, that is the relationship between wages and prices.

475
00:59:22,000 --> 00:59:34,000
 And if you want, in other words, the possibility that high inflation will ignite wage price spiral, whatever you want to define it.

476
00:59:34,000 --> 00:59:45,000
 Here we have some evidence that suggests that in a low inflation regime, wages are less sensitive to inflation and vice versa.

477
00:59:45,000 --> 00:59:57,000
 The left-hand panel of this graph shows an estimate of the sensitivity of wage growth to past inflation that's based on advanced economy data.

478
00:59:57,000 --> 01:00:00,000
 And we have different overlapping sample periods.

479
01:00:00,000 --> 01:00:12,000
 You see that the sensitivity is positive and statistically significant up to the moment where the '80s and the '70s exit the estimation sample.

480
01:00:12,000 --> 01:00:19,000
 We achieve some low level of inflation.

481
01:00:19,000 --> 01:00:31,000
 And the similar considerations apply on the right-hand panel for what concerns the sensitivity of inflation to past wage growth.

482
01:00:31,000 --> 01:00:37,000
 So let me skip that one in the interest of time.

483
01:00:37,000 --> 01:00:42,000
 That's some other insights on wage price relationship.

484
01:00:42,000 --> 01:00:50,000
 So this brings me to the question that we're trying to tackle in the panel, that is where do we stand now and what is the outlook of inflation?

485
01:00:50,000 --> 01:00:59,000
 So at the BIS we don't have our own forecast of inflation, so we just try to provide more of insights if you want.

486
01:00:59,000 --> 01:01:18,000
 And based on what I said, here the insight is that the outlook for inflation looking ahead is clearly determined and shaped by whether we are in a low inflation regime as we were pre-COVID or we are transitioning towards a high inflation regime.

487
01:01:18,000 --> 01:01:30,000
 So what I will try to point here is some insights into this very difficult question.

488
01:01:30,000 --> 01:01:45,000
 As I said, one key defining feature of a low inflation regime is that there is little price similarity across price changes in different sectors.

489
01:01:45,000 --> 01:01:52,000
 This is indeed something that you can clearly appreciate from the left-hand panel of this graph.

490
01:01:52,000 --> 01:02:14,000
 Here we plot on the y-axis an index of similarity in price changes for a bunch of advanced and emerging market economies and for a sample period that depends on the individual data availability but covers both high and low inflation phases.

491
01:02:14,000 --> 01:02:21,000
 And this is plot against the level of inflation on the x-axis.

492
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:26,000
 So you see that there is a clear positive relationship between these two variables.

493
01:02:26,000 --> 01:02:36,000
 And it's even stronger, it gets stronger and stronger as inflation increases, of course, and it applies to both advanced and emerging market economies.

494
01:02:36,000 --> 01:02:52,000
 So this index of similarity is something we can try to gauge whether we're moving towards a high inflation regime or, if you want, if risks of transitioning towards a high inflation regime are actually growing.

495
01:02:52,000 --> 01:02:57,000
 And this is something we show in the right-hand panel of this graph.

496
01:02:57,000 --> 01:03:12,000
 So here the box and whiskers red plots correspond to the historical distribution of the similarity index between 2012 and 2019.

497
01:03:12,000 --> 01:03:22,000
 And then the orange dots and the blue dots represent respectively the readings in 2021 and 2022 of, say, the index.

498
01:03:22,000 --> 01:03:35,000
 You see that throughout 2021, the orange dots were more or less in line with the historical distribution, although a bit skewed towards the upper tail.

499
01:03:35,000 --> 01:03:52,000
 And in 2022, especially in advanced economies, there are clear signs that these measures of the similarity index are going a bit off the historical values.

500
01:03:52,000 --> 01:04:07,000
 So this is potentially a sign that risks of transitioning towards a high inflation regime and therefore having all the negative effects of a high inflation regime are growing.

501
01:04:07,000 --> 01:04:21,000
 And another reflection of these growing risks is the increasing persistence of inflation, which here we show for both advanced and emerging market economies in relationship to the persistence of inflation.

502
01:04:21,000 --> 01:04:34,000
 In the pre-COVID years, you see that most of the points are above the 45 degrees line, signaling that current estimates of persistence are ticking up.

503
01:04:34,000 --> 01:04:38,000
 That's another sign that things are moving.

504
01:04:38,000 --> 01:04:47,000
 Now, let me wrap up and recap what I just said.

505
01:04:47,000 --> 01:05:12,000
 So what we try to do in this work is to characterize inflation in terms of two regimes with a view that this characterization, which is largely based on a granular approach to look at different sectoral prices, can provide useful insights in the current conditions.

506
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:24,000
 Now, of course, the key challenge, and that's something for which we don't have an answer, is that the transitions between one regime and the other are inherently uncertain.

507
01:05:24,000 --> 01:05:37,000
 And there's no reliable, fully reliable real-time indicator that tells you whether you are in a regime or in the other one or at what point of the transition you might be.

508
01:05:37,000 --> 01:05:53,000
 And this is especially problematic because if you want, if you have established that you are in one regime or the other, you can use historical evidence, if available, to figure out where inflation is heading.

509
01:05:53,000 --> 01:05:56,000
 And when it's heading and when it's going to come back.

510
01:05:56,000 --> 01:06:02,000
 During a transition, it is much more difficult because there's no standard model that can accommodate these two different states of the world.

511
01:06:02,000 --> 01:06:20,000
 So the policy implications that we draw from this work and from these considerations is that in a world in which transitions are getting increasingly risky and increasingly threatening,

512
01:06:20,000 --> 01:06:25,000
 sound judgment in the conduct of monetary policy comes at the premium.

513
01:06:25,000 --> 01:06:36,000
 So far, central banks have acted forcefully and reacted promptly to the growing inflation pressures.

514
01:06:36,000 --> 01:06:47,000
 So this is part of what we refer to as sound judgment and promptness in action to respond to challenges.

515
01:06:47,000 --> 01:06:49,000
 I think I can stop here.

516
01:06:49,000 --> 01:06:50,000
 Thank you.

517
01:06:50,000 --> 01:06:51,000
 Thank you.

518
01:06:51,000 --> 01:06:52,000
 Thank you.

519
01:06:52,000 --> 01:06:53,000
 Thank you.

520
01:06:53,000 --> 01:07:00,000
 And finally, let's have a view from the private sector.

521
01:07:00,000 --> 01:07:01,000
 Andres.

522
01:07:01,000 --> 01:07:01,000
 All right.

523
01:07:01,000 --> 01:07:01,000
 Good morning all.

524
01:07:01,000 --> 01:07:27,000
 Thanks for the governor and thanks for the central bank for inviting me back.

525
01:07:27,000 --> 01:07:29,000
 That's typically a good sign.

526
01:07:29,000 --> 01:07:30,000
 So let's see next year.

527
01:07:30,000 --> 01:07:42,000
 And the reason that I'm saying that is I guess that we're slightly more skeptical on what you've heard so far.

528
01:07:42,000 --> 01:07:48,000
 I'm not trying to be too skeptical, but I want to show a couple of wrinkles here that I think matter.

529
01:07:48,000 --> 01:07:55,000
 So there's a bunch of charts that you will have seen now different variations of so I'll go through quickly.

530
01:07:55,000 --> 01:08:04,000
 The bottom line of this chart and the next chart is essentially that inflation expectations headline inflation expectations are anchored.

531
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:20,000
 And another way is sort of what we did on the left here is pulling together the forecasts of sort of the institutions here on the panel that actually do forecast headline inflation.

532
01:08:20,000 --> 01:08:27,000
 So we see that the ECB is a touch lower than the fund and where we are.

533
01:08:27,000 --> 01:08:36,000
 And then on the right, we also show you a chart that actually focuses in on core inflation, which, you know, we think the action really is.

534
01:08:36,000 --> 01:08:46,000
 So that's the interesting economic conversation when you're coming out of an energy price structure sort of whipping headline inflation all over the place for a number of years.

535
01:08:46,000 --> 01:09:03,000
 So the point of the right chart is that if you compare the ECB forecast both in the December round or projection round and in the March round, is that we're, you know, 30, 40 basis points above.

536
01:09:03,000 --> 01:09:08,000
 And that includes the end of the forecast horizon.

537
01:09:08,000 --> 01:09:29,000
 And the point I'm trying to make here is that this is probably one of the very few instances in economics where 20 basis points, so call it 2.2 as a core inflation forecast a few years out, is significantly different from two.

538
01:09:29,000 --> 01:09:36,000
 Not so much because of the estimate, but because of the policy communication that is behind it.

539
01:09:36,000 --> 01:09:46,000
 So why is monetary policy tricky right now?

540
01:09:46,000 --> 01:09:52,000
 Why is this inflationary process not straightforward?

541
01:09:52,000 --> 01:09:58,000
 So on the left, we just want to zoom in a little bit to give you a flavor for what's going on here.

542
01:09:58,000 --> 01:10:09,000
 So on the left, you have core inflation, the darker line, and that is going down during the course of this year, but there's a bump in the summer.

543
01:10:09,000 --> 01:10:18,000
 And that bump in the summer has to do with sort of one off effects both last year, so base effects, but then also this year.

544
01:10:18,000 --> 01:10:28,000
 And that has to do again with something very specific, namely the introduction of subsidized transport tickets, general transport ticket in Germany.

545
01:10:28,000 --> 01:10:40,000
 So you can see that single policy measures really have a massive impact on the Eurozone wide core inflation trajectory.

546
01:10:40,000 --> 01:10:51,000
 And so I think the takeaway here is that this is what makes communicating about monetary policy and also sort of thinking about the macroeconomics behind it in the context of core inflation particularly tricky.

547
01:10:51,000 --> 01:11:09,000
 So if you take out transport from Eurozone core inflation, so this is all our internal forecasts, then you see that the decline is relatively monotonous.

548
01:11:09,000 --> 01:11:14,000
 Whereas if you leave it in, you have a bump that you need to explain if you want to go there.

549
01:11:14,000 --> 01:11:25,000
 And so that's one sort of element of why sort of this disinflationary process is quite tricky and not straightforward to communicate.

550
01:11:25,000 --> 01:11:31,000
 On the right, you see a chart that, you know, a number of speakers have already talked about in many ways,

551
01:11:31,000 --> 01:11:36,000
 and that is sort of service inflation being the last man standing, if you want, for an inflationary process.

552
01:11:36,000 --> 01:11:41,000
 Up until a little while, there was also non-energy industrial goods inflation.

553
01:11:41,000 --> 01:11:46,000
 But that has, you know, presumably turned.

554
01:11:46,000 --> 01:11:51,000
 But service inflation was still waiting for that to turn.

555
01:11:51,000 --> 01:12:01,000
 Now, yes, inflation, including core inflation, will go lower.

556
01:12:01,000 --> 01:12:04,000
 The question is how confident can we be?

557
01:12:04,000 --> 01:12:14,000
 So, the ECB publishes a significant number of underlying inflation measures, and they probably produce many more that they don't publish.

558
01:12:14,000 --> 01:12:23,000
 In this chart, I have used a few that they -- one that they publish, two that they publish, and a couple that are -- that we do on the side.

559
01:12:23,000 --> 01:12:38,000
 And essentially, the idea here is that sort of the underlying sort of leading measures like the PCCI in yellow show you that there should be a turning point in core inflation.

560
01:12:38,000 --> 01:12:44,000
 Now, this is up to March, and I don't think that this picture looks particularly convincing about that turning point.

561
01:12:44,000 --> 01:12:59,000
 So, now, if you add April data -- see what I did here? Very fancy -- you know, I think you can be ever so slightly more positive about the dynamic.

562
01:12:59,000 --> 01:13:14,000
 But it's still not, you know, a slam dunk that we're going to go lower and to target in a reasonable amount of time.

563
01:13:14,000 --> 01:13:21,000
 Now, we've also already talked about a couple of interesting factors, distinguishing factors on core inflation.

564
01:13:21,000 --> 01:13:29,000
 I think here, to recap, the wages obviously play a significant role in this process.

565
01:13:29,000 --> 01:13:40,000
 Typically, the narrative is that a 3% wage increase is consistent with 2% core inflation four quarters later or something along those lines.

566
01:13:40,000 --> 01:13:52,000
 Now, the problem that we have is that the ECB's forecast for employee compensation two years out in 2025 is still 3.5%.

567
01:13:52,000 --> 01:13:55,000
 And Philip showed you that in a chart.

568
01:13:55,000 --> 01:14:07,000
 Now, we also believe that that might be low-balling it a little bit in the sense that wage dynamics in certain countries have probably surprised to the upside over the last few months.

569
01:14:07,000 --> 01:14:11,000
 So we actually see that getting revised up.

570
01:14:11,000 --> 01:14:17,000
 Now, we've also talked about margins that are quite high, profit margins that are quite high,

571
01:14:17,000 --> 01:14:23,000
 and that should enable real wages to grow while not having a large impact on inflation.

572
01:14:23,000 --> 01:14:32,000
 And that's true, but I think the takeaway here is that this is quite differentiated across countries.

573
01:14:32,000 --> 01:14:46,000
 So on the left, I'm showing you here wages in the dashed lines are wages, where you see Germany wages have been shot up quite a bit.

574
01:14:46,000 --> 01:14:49,000
 But also Italian wages now slowly starting to creep up.

575
01:14:49,000 --> 01:14:56,000
 So one of the big surprises coming out of this COVID shock was that Italian wages didn't really do much in response to inflation.

576
01:14:56,000 --> 01:15:00,000
 It has to do with the way the indexation works.

577
01:15:00,000 --> 01:15:03,000
 But, you know, now they're starting to pick up.

578
01:15:03,000 --> 01:15:06,000
 So the question is, how much are they going to pick up?

579
01:15:06,000 --> 01:15:16,000
 The solid lines on the left is sort of something that we constructed as a simplistic measure of profit margin or pricing power, if you want.

580
01:15:16,000 --> 01:15:23,000
 And that has obviously gone down a lot during the pandemic and has been coming back up.

581
01:15:23,000 --> 01:15:34,000
 And that is, if you want the cross-country way of looking this, that Philip showed you the cross-sectoral way of looking it.

582
01:15:34,000 --> 01:15:39,000
 So agriculture, energy, where profit margins have been particularly high.

583
01:15:39,000 --> 01:15:41,000
 Now, why am I showing this?

584
01:15:41,000 --> 01:15:46,000
 Because this is what makes monetary policy right now very complicated.

585
01:15:46,000 --> 01:16:01,000
 And it makes sort of the amount of certainty that you need to be convinced that inflation comes back to the target in a timely manner quite complicated.

586
01:16:01,000 --> 01:16:10,000
 The chart on the right makes precisely that point in the sense that the German manufacturing margin.

587
01:16:10,000 --> 01:16:18,000
 So this is a measure that essentially compares output prices with input prices in the purchasing manager index data.

588
01:16:18,000 --> 01:16:30,000
 So this is essentially the impression that purchasing managers have on what they can push through in terms of output prices versus what they need to take in terms of input prices.

589
01:16:30,000 --> 01:16:35,000
 That that has rebounded quite a bit in specific sectors in specific countries.

590
01:16:35,000 --> 01:16:37,000
 For example, Germany manufacturing.

591
01:16:37,000 --> 01:16:43,000
 But that's not the case elsewhere where it has just sort of come back to normal.

592
01:16:43,000 --> 01:17:00,000
 So the takeaway here is that this disinflationary process that we're talking about is quite complex, both in terms of the mechanics of it, near term, medium term, and also a large variation across countries,

593
01:17:00,000 --> 01:17:12,000
 which the ECB obviously cannot -- well, needs to take into account, but cannot really speak too much about, because the ECB looks at aggregate data, and that's the job definition.

594
01:17:12,000 --> 01:17:19,000
 So I guess the takeaway here is that -- oh, yeah, that's the slide you've all been waiting for.

595
01:17:19,000 --> 01:17:28,000
 The takeaway really overall is that, yes, from a market side, we agree that inflation is going to come lower.

596
01:17:28,000 --> 01:17:33,000
 In fact, that is what's priced into inflation markets which deal with headline inflation.

597
01:17:33,000 --> 01:17:42,000
 But I think the underlying narrative in terms of core inflation and core inflation dynamics and what goes into it is a lot more complicated.

598
01:17:42,000 --> 01:17:50,000
 And so to the extent that that matters in terms of monetary policy communications, we're in a very, very tricky spot.

599
01:17:50,000 --> 01:18:05,000
 And we would probably -- net net, we would probably think that inflation comes down a little bit less quickly than what you've heard so far from the other speakers.

600
01:18:05,000 --> 01:18:06,000
 Thank you, Andres.

601
01:18:06,000 --> 01:18:06,000
 Thank you, Andres.

602
01:18:06,000 --> 01:18:06,000
 Thank you, Andres.

